7
00:00:15,410 --> 00:00:16,410
Sierra Leone.

8
00:00:16,410 --> 00:00:18,040
A country in West Africa more or less

9
00:00:18,040 --> 00:00:19,530
the size of South Carolina.

10
00:00:19,530 --> 00:00:22,500
In fact, it’s kind of what South Carolina
sees

11
00:00:22,500 --> 00:00:24,320
when it looks in the mirror.

12
00:00:24,320 --> 00:00:25,330
But unlike South Carolina,

13
00:00:25,330 --> 00:00:29,030
where the average life expectancy is 77 years,

14
00:00:29,030 --> 00:00:31,920
people in Sierra Leone live to an average
of just 52.

15
00:00:31,920 --> 00:00:35,839
Still, that’s a LOT better than in 1995,

16
00:00:35,839 --> 00:00:39,920
when Sierra Leone was in the middle of a bloody
10-year civil war a

17
00:00:39,920 --> 00:00:42,280
nd people barely made it to age 35.

18
00:00:42,280 --> 00:00:44,940
“We were coming through town,

19
00:00:44,940 --> 00:00:46,530
searching for food,

20
00:00:46,530 --> 00:00:50,260
when they got all of us. T

21
00:00:50,260 --> 00:00:53,449
hey captured us in an ambush.

22
00:00:53,449 --> 00:00:56,109
They captured all of us.

23
00:00:56,109 --> 00:00:58,730
They assembled seven of us. Six were killed.”

24
00:00:58,730 --> 00:01:00,739
Luckily that’s all in the past.

25
00:01:00,739 --> 00:01:02,709
Still, to this day Sierra Leone remains

26
00:01:02,709 --> 00:01:05,540
one of the poorest countries in Africa.

27
00:01:05,540 --> 00:01:08,439
More than half the population lives below
the poverty line

28
00:01:08,439 --> 00:01:10,939
of one dollar twenty five cents a day.

29
00:01:10,939 --> 00:01:14,140
But recently, things seem to be looking up
for Sierra Leone.

30
00:01:14,140 --> 00:01:19,180
“We are a successful modern, stable democracy.

31
00:01:19,180 --> 00:01:22,840
One that has evolved and matured over 20 years

32
00:01:22,840 --> 00:01:27,289
from chaos and lawlessness of civil conflict.”

33
00:01:27,289 --> 00:01:28,780
That was the country’s new president,

34
00:01:28,780 --> 00:01:30,039
Julius Maada Bio,

35
00:01:30,039 --> 00:01:31,600
elected in April.

36
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:32,600
Here he is in China…

37
00:01:32,600 --> 00:01:35,189
...at the recent Forum on China-Africa Cooperation,

38
00:01:35,189 --> 00:01:37,109
where Chinese leader Xi Jinping pledged

39
00:01:37,109 --> 00:01:40,299
$60 billion dollars of loans to Africa.

40
00:01:40,299 --> 00:01:42,689
But President Bio made headlines last week

41
00:01:42,689 --> 00:01:45,689
when he overturned a huge deal with China

42
00:01:45,689 --> 00:01:48,159
hat his predecessor Ernest Bai Koroma…

43
00:01:48,159 --> 00:01:50,500
...signed a few years back.

44
00:01:50,500 --> 00:01:51,909
The plan was for a Chinese company

45
00:01:51,909 --> 00:01:54,280
to build the Mamamah International Airport…

46
00:01:54,280 --> 00:01:56,399
...with funding from a Chinese state-owned
bank

47
00:01:56,399 --> 00:01:58,840
to the tune of 312 million dollars.

48
00:01:58,840 --> 00:02:02,429
A third of that was to be from a loan that
Sierra Leone

49
00:02:02,429 --> 00:02:04,369
would have to pay back.

50
00:02:04,369 --> 00:02:07,350
Sierra Leone’s Minister of Transport and
Aviation

51
00:02:07,350 --> 00:02:10,600
announced the project’s cancellation in
a letter,

52
00:02:10,600 --> 00:02:12,610
part of which was published in the Daily Nation,

53
00:02:12,610 --> 00:02:14,610
a Kenyan newspaper.

54
00:02:14,610 --> 00:02:16,780
So instead of taking out a massive loan to
build

55
00:02:16,780 --> 00:02:19,280
a brand new airport that it doesn’t need,

56
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:23,050
Sierra Leone is going to fix up the one it
already has.

57
00:02:23,050 --> 00:02:24,840
That seems like a prudent choice,

58
00:02:24,840 --> 00:02:27,340
given that a recent IMF mission to Sierra
Leone

59
00:02:27,340 --> 00:02:30,990
found that “the economic environment remains
challenging”

60
00:02:30,990 --> 00:02:32,620
and hailed the new government’s efforts
to

61
00:02:32,620 --> 00:02:36,790
“stabilize public debt and reduce it to
sustainable levels,

62
00:02:36,790 --> 00:02:38,800
and prioritize public investment aimed at

63
00:02:38,800 --> 00:02:41,260
reducing social and infrastructure gaps.”

64
00:02:41,260 --> 00:02:45,050
It also turns out that an earlier 200 million
loan from China

65
00:02:45,050 --> 00:02:48,060
for the same proposed new airport was cancelled

66
00:02:48,060 --> 00:02:50,030
when the IMF and World Bank

67
00:02:50,030 --> 00:02:53,540
did a debt sustainability analysis of Sierra
Leone,

68
00:02:53,540 --> 00:02:57,030
and expressed “strong concerns” about
the deal.

69
00:02:57,030 --> 00:02:59,680
And when a formal organization like the IMF

70
00:02:59,680 --> 00:03:02,290
says it has “strong concerns”,

71
00:03:02,290 --> 00:03:05,260
in normal language that means “run!”

72
00:03:05,260 --> 00:03:07,950
The risk of taking a loan from China is,

73
00:03:07,950 --> 00:03:09,150
let’s say,

74
00:03:09,150 --> 00:03:11,770
different from taking an IMF loan.

75
00:03:11,770 --> 00:03:14,300
If you can’t afford to pay back an IMF loan,

76
00:03:14,300 --> 00:03:15,810
they may impose some conditions

77
00:03:15,810 --> 00:03:18,560
before bailing you out with another loan.

78
00:03:18,560 --> 00:03:19,980
Those conditions might include

79
00:03:19,980 --> 00:03:22,450
making you adopt free market reforms,

80
00:03:22,450 --> 00:03:26,490
clamp down on corruption, or strengthen rule-of-law
institutions.

81
00:03:26,490 --> 00:03:29,050
But those are generally things that make a
country better,

82
00:03:29,050 --> 00:03:31,770
and can attract future investment.

83
00:03:31,770 --> 00:03:35,200
But if you owe China money and can’t afford
to pay up,

84
00:03:35,200 --> 00:03:37,570
well, they take their pound of flesh.

85
00:03:37,570 --> 00:03:38,710
Like Djibouti.

86
00:03:38,710 --> 00:03:40,820
The African country of Djibouti.

87
00:03:40,820 --> 00:03:43,210
China recently set up a military base there—

88
00:03:43,210 --> 00:03:44,870
likely through political pressure.

89
00:03:44,870 --> 00:03:49,090
China is also helping finance the main seaport
in Djibouti.

90
00:03:49,090 --> 00:03:51,330
But if it can’t pay off its debt—

91
00:03:51,330 --> 00:03:52,590
and that seems likely—

92
00:03:52,590 --> 00:03:56,200
it may be forced to hand over its port to
China.

93
00:03:56,200 --> 00:03:57,930
And this means China would control

94
00:03:57,930 --> 00:04:01,490
the key access point in and out of Djibouti.

95
00:04:01,490 --> 00:04:03,890
The big fear is that as China hands out loans

96
00:04:03,890 --> 00:04:06,680
for huge infrastructure projects around the
world

97
00:04:06,680 --> 00:04:08,900
as part of its Belt and Road Initiative,

98
00:04:08,900 --> 00:04:11,360
it will use the loans that countries can’t
afford t

99
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:15,060
o pay back as a way to take resources or territory.

100
00:04:15,060 --> 00:04:17,930
But by bucking that trend, Sierra Leone

101
00:04:17,930 --> 00:04:21,280
has just become the first African country
to sidestep

102
00:04:21,280 --> 00:04:24,130
one of China’s potential debt traps.

103
00:04:24,130 --> 00:04:26,510
Some experts even say that Sierra Leone may
be

104
00:04:26,510 --> 00:04:30,000
the first of a series of dominos that are
about to fall.

105
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:34,000
A professor at a college in North Carolina
says this cancellation

106
00:04:34,000 --> 00:04:36,270
is a sign that African countries are are starting
to

107
00:04:36,270 --> 00:04:39,660
wise up when it comes to the threat of Chinese
loans.

108
00:04:39,660 --> 00:04:42,230
Now after the Mamamah airport deal was axed,

109
00:04:42,230 --> 00:04:44,750
China was quick to say “nothing to see here,
folks.”

110
00:04:44,750 --> 00:04:47,740
“I don’t think this particular project
should be overblown

111
